1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,395
We've arrived at the final stage of data wrangling; data cleaning.

2
00:00:04,395 --> 00:00:08,490
By now you've already gathered your data and assessed it for any issues.

3
00:00:08,490 --> 00:00:11,040
In this lesson we're going to be talking about remediating

4
00:00:11,040 --> 00:00:14,490
these issues so that the data is then cleaned and good to go,

5
00:00:14,490 --> 00:00:18,180
ready to pass the downstream stakeholders for tasks like making

6
00:00:18,180 --> 00:00:22,350
visualizations or training machine learning models out of the data that you've gotten.

7
00:00:22,350 --> 00:00:24,360
Data cleaning is often one of

8
00:00:24,360 --> 00:00:28,005
the most time-consuming steps of the data wrangling process.

9
00:00:28,005 --> 00:00:30,390
Why? Well, there are a number of reasons.

10
00:00:30,390 --> 00:00:35,175
First, it's impossible to clean all the identified issues simultaneously.

11
00:00:35,175 --> 00:00:38,840
You need to methodologically address each dimension of issues in

12
00:00:38,840 --> 00:00:40,700
your dataset and then reassess

13
00:00:40,700 --> 00:00:44,050
those issues to confirm that you've resolved them appropriately.

14
00:00:44,050 --> 00:00:46,880
Once issues in one-dimension is resolved,

15
00:00:46,880 --> 00:00:50,650
you can proceed to tackle the next one in a systematic manner.

16
00:00:50,650 --> 00:00:55,205
Second, many of the issues may surface during the data cleaning phase,

17
00:00:55,205 --> 00:00:58,190
and require you to go back and reassess the data to

18
00:00:58,190 --> 00:01:01,505
ensure that you can address and resolve these problems appropriately.

19
00:01:01,505 --> 00:01:03,980
This iterative process is time-consuming,

20
00:01:03,980 --> 00:01:07,290
but it helps maintain data quality throughout the analysis.

21
00:01:07,290 --> 00:01:11,375
The different types of data can complicate things further.

22
00:01:11,375 --> 00:01:14,000
In this lesson, we'll be going over how to clean

23
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:17,000
data for tabular time series and text data.

24
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:20,090
So you can understand how to generalize and apply

25
00:01:20,090 --> 00:01:24,450
considerations for cleaning data to different datatypes.

